</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="46" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1323,524,670]" box="[264,407,524,549]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis box="[264,407,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1323,524,670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
New World, primarily Neotropical. One species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharkey" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="Sharkey" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[936,1283,564,589]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Austroearinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufofemoratus" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[936,1283,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Austroearinus rufofemoratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="9" pageNumber="46" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">n. comb.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is widespread in central and eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[801,860,604,630]" name="United States of America" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">USA</collectingCountry>
and through Central America, but the genus is far more diverse in warm tropical areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1324,724,1110]" box="[264,460,724,749]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis box="[264,460,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Species diversity</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1324,724,1110]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
At least two species formerly placed in other agathidine genera belong here: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharkey" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="Sharkey" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[264,615,804,829]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Austroearinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufofemoratus">
<emphasis box="[264,615,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Austroearinus rufofemoratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, originally placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Muesebeck 1927)" authorityName="Muesebeck" authorityYear="1927" baseAuthorityName="Muesebeck" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[918,1255,804,830]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Bassus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[918,999,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Bassus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Muesebeck, C. F. W." box="[1028,1246,804,830]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 73" refId="ref6487" refString="Muesebeck, C. F. W. (1927) A revision of the parasitic wasps of the subfamily Braconinae occurring in America north of Mexico. Proceedings of the United States National Museum. 69 (2642), 1 - 73." type="journal article" year="1927">Muesebeck 1927</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and subsequently transferred to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Sharkey 2004)" authorityName="Sharkey" authorityYear="2004" baseAuthorityName="Sharkey" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[593,880,844,870]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Earinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[593,686,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Earinus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sharkey, M. J." box="[703,873,844,870]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" pagination="134 - 152" refId="ref6898" refString="Sharkey, M. J. (2004) Synopsis of the Agathidinae (Hymenoptera: Braconidae) of America north of Mexico. Trudy Russkago Entomologicheskago Obshchestva. [Horae Societatis Entomologicae Rossicae.] 75 (1), 134 - 152." type="journal article" year="2004">Sharkey 2004</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schrottkey)" authorityName="Sharkey" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="Schrottkey" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[894,1323,844,870]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Austroearinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unicolor" status="n. comb.">
<emphasis box="[894,1166,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Austroearinus unicolor</emphasis>
(Schrottkey)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[264,371,884,910]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,371,884,910]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">n. comb.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, originally placed in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schrottkey 1902)" authorityName="Schrottkey" authorityYear="1902" baseAuthorityName="Schrottkey" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[623,936,884,910]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Orgilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[623,711,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Orgilus</emphasis>
(Schrottkey 1902)
</taxonomicName>
, but more recently considered as a member of the genus 
<emphasis box="[541,631,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muesebeck" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[541,626,924,949]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Bassus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Bassus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The genus is extremely species rich. I estimate there to be more than 100 species and perhaps several times this number. Many species also appear to be common, for example, there has been intensive Malaise trap sampling in La Selva, 
<collectingCountry box="[264,393,1044,1070]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
for more than a decade (http://viceroy.eeb.uconn.edu/ALAS/ALAS.html) and, of all species of 
<taxonomicName box="[456,602,1084,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Agathidinae">Agathidinae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharkey" authorityYear="2006" box="[614,788,1084,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Austroearinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysokeras">
<emphasis box="[614,788,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">A. chrysokeras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been the most frequently collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="46" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1325,1164,1630]" box="[264,679,1164,1189]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis box="[264,679,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Biology (Dan Janzen, pers. comm.)</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1325,1164,1630]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
A specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharkey" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="Sharkey" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[499,700,1204,1229]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Austroearinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufofemoratus">
<emphasis box="[499,700,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">A. rufofemoratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[778,1030,1204,1230]" country="Costa Rica" name="Guanacaste" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Guanacaste Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1045,1179,1204,1230]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, was reared from a microlepidopteran, only identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[800,932,1244,1270]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
, feeding on the mature leaves of 
<taxonomicName box="[264,444,1284,1309]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Amyris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pinnata">
<emphasis box="[264,444,1284,1309]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Amyris pinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="1789" box="[458,569,1284,1310]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rutaceae</taxonomicName>
) and living in a light silk web. The wasp larva emerged from the last instar caterpillar on 
<date box="[552,704,1324,1350]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="2002-04-06">6 April 2002</date>
and spun a strong white cocoon tightly glued to the leaf surface. This is unlike other known agathidines which spin inside the caterpillar cocoon. The wasp eclosed 9 days later, which means that all of this happened in the full dry season. The site is 
<quantity box="[533,608,1444,1470]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" unit="m" value="280.0">280 m</quantity>
elevation, Lat 11.04562 Long 足85.45742, and locally known as Puente Mena in the Del Oro property adjacent to the north boundary of the Area de Conservacion 
<collectingRegion box="[436,575,1524,1550]" country="Costa Rica" name="Guanacaste" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Guanacaste</collectingRegion>
. The site lies on the interface between ACG dry forests and ACG rain forest. The entire record may be found at http://janzen.sas.upenn.edu, refer to specimen number 02足SRNP足14223.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="46" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1323,1684,1790]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis box="[264,389,1684,1709]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Etymology</emphasis>
From the Latin 
<emphasis box="[499,602,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">australis</emphasis>
which means southern, referring to the southern distribution of this genus and its morphological similarity to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sharkey" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[834,927,1764,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Earinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[834,927,1764,1789]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Earinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
